l and postcolonial history of the continent.The war novel, Coundouriotis argues, stakes claims to collective rights that contrast with the individualism of the bildungsroman tradition. The genre is a form of people’s history that participates in a political struggle for the rights of the dispossessed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAfrican fiction (English)xHistory and criticism. 0aAfrican fiction (French)xHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature and societyzAfrica. 0aWar in literature. 4aAfrican Studies. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / African.2bisacsh  aAfrica.  aHuman Rights.  aWar novel.  agender.  ahumanitarianism.  anaturalism.  apeople's history.  apostcolonial studies.  awar.  aworld novel.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311072903040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823262359zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823262359423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823262359/original  a978-3-11-072903-0  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK